### 1.2 Deterministic jitter rule (declared, byte-stable)

| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Seed | 12345 |
| LCG multiplier | 1103515245 |
| LCG increment | 12345 |
| LCG mask | `0x7FFFFFFF` |
| Jitter fraction of local spacing | 0.30 |
| Domain clamp margin fraction | 0.05 |

Rule: preserve endpoints. For each interior coordinate `i ∈ 1..n−2`: advance LCG, derive `rand_unit ∈ [0, 1)`, apply `offset = 0.30 × local_spacing × (rand_unit − 0.5)` where `local_spacing = (canonical[i+1] − canonical[i−1]) / 2`. Clamp strictly inside the open domain with a 5% margin. The LCG is byte-stable across Python versions. (Test 4 enforces endpoint preservation + domain interior.)

### 1.3 Bin rule (fixed cuts, not refit)

For comparability across grids, the **canonical-grid tercile edges on `log10(radicand_magnitude)` from Phase 2b** are applied as **fixed cuts** to the jittered grid:

| Fixture | t1 (log10 radicand) | t2 (log10 radicand) |
|---|---|---|
| `sr_four_form` | −1.14 | −0.20 |
| `schwarzschild_four_form` | −1.74 | −0.78 |
| `pure_algebraic_four_form` | −0.59 | −0.20 |

Bin labels (`T1_small_radicand`, `T2_intermediate_radicand`, `T3_large_radicand`) therefore mean the same numeric thing on both grids; per-bin stability is well-posed.

